column3: Shashank Rammoorthy
column5: Domain-Agnostic Benchmark for Self-Supervised Learning - writing a JAX codebase
column6:
The use of self-supervised learning (SSL) algorithms has been on the rise across the machine learning community. SSL helps models acquire useful information from unlabelled data and then use this information to perform downstream tasks. The common paradigm here is to ‚Äòpretrain‚Äô on a large general dataset and then ‚Äòfinetune‚Äô on a more specialized, typically smaller dataset.
The Domain-Agnostic Benchmark for Self-Supervised Learning (DABS) was published in NeurIPS last year, and has served as a benchmark for self-supervised learning algorithms. Specifically, to perform well on DABS, an algorithm must be pretrained on six unlabeled datasets from different domains: natural images, text, speech recordings, medical imaging, multichannel sensor data and image-text pairs.
(Tamkin et al.)
Through this Senior Project, I implemented a system for fast and large scale training of self-supervised learning algorithms with DABS. Specifically, I designed and wrote a JAX codebase for DABS ‚Äî enabling us to run baseline algorithms on Google Cloud Tensor Processing Units, or TPUs, and have an order of magnitude faster training times.

column3: Luca Pistor, Nathan Bhak
column6: Research interest in Internet measurement has grown immensely since the development of zmap, a stateless Internet-scale port scanner. Similarly, the presence of TCP services running on unexpected (or un-assigned) ports indicates a ‚Äúlong tail‚Äù of services which often have a considerably weaker security posture. In this work, we develop a UDP fingerprinting module for zmap that allows researchers to determine the distribution of UDP services running on unexpected ports

column3: Max Pike
column4: Ali Mirzazadeh, Krish Maniar, Florian Dubost, Christopher Lee-Messer, Daniel Rubin
column5: Enforcing Attention Map Consistency for Unsupervised Finetuning
column6: In many industry computer vision tasks, large, labeled datasets are hard to come by. Therefore, when it comes to training deep neural networks, they have a hard time learning meaningful representations from the dataset. One way to visualize these models is through calculation of "attention maps" that display which parts of the input were important in making the associated prediction. Attention maps can be calculated in different ways, and as a result, do not always agree with each other. This problem becomes exacerbated when the model is overfitting to a small dataset. As a result, the QIAI lab proposes an unsupervised learning objective to be used as a fine-tuning step, where we calculate attention maps with 2 different algorithms and enforce a similarity metric between them.

column3: Krishnan Nair, Stephanie Hu, Rick Robert, Derian Williams, Adonis Pugh
column6: DAHA is a mobile app that allows Stanford students to sell, rent, and buy goods on campus quickly and efficiently. Our product was inspired by DAHA requests in dorm chats, as well as the need for seniors to sell their belongings before graduating to underclassmen that wish to purchase common goods for their college experience at a cheaper price. We envision this as a marketplace for all Stanford students, which extends the reach of DAHA requests beyond a single dorm. In this marketplace, users can enter items that they are seeking (a DAHA request). All users will have access to the requests, allowing them to see which items are in demand. If they have something being requested and wish to sell it, they can create a DAWA post about their item and name their price. Even if a user doesn't wish to make a DAHA, they can enter the marketplace and see what items are up for sale. By understanding what items are in demand and being requested, we hope to encourage the recycling of goods at Stanford.

column6: The Honest Protocol is an ecosystem for decentralized audits of digital assets on Ethereum. It allows for a decentralized, validated database in which NFTs are labeled with honesty/anti-scam-related traits. This is necessary in a world in which NFT scams are rampant, and users do not know which proejcts to trust. Our project included two main parts: the smart contracts (deployed on an Ethereum testnet) and an API to interpret the smart contracts.

column3: Samaksh Goyal, Mark Rau, Doug James
column6:
In this project we aim to establish the relationship between the
construction of an acoustic guitar and the resulting frequency and
amplitude response. The forward modeling problem is to take as
input the physical material parameters and geometry of a guitar
and use FEM methods to perform modal analysis. This part involves
modeling the guitar meshing, elasticity coefficients for the wood,
and different boundary conditions. The inverse problem (the more
interesting case) is to take as input the a user defined ‚Äúsound‚Äù and
find the best parameters for a guitar that would produce such a
sound

column5: Kara : A social network to reduce the world's inequality
column6:
Kara aims to revolutionize the donation experience of people worldwide. 

Kara is designed as a social network that connects donors (mentors) with people in need of financial help (prot√©g√©s). Prot√©g√©s and mentors are matched based on their preferences and can form a personal relationship through private messaging and interaction via social feeds. Mentors can directly send money to their prot√©g√©s, helping them achieve their basic needs. Once that need is met, mentors get notified via a picture, call or video, which allows them to directly see the impact of their donation. 

Kara aims to increase worldwide donations by providing an intuitive platform with mechanisms designed to incentivize donors to give more.

column6: Analytics are crucial to baseball front offices, helping management measure the true impact of players and coaches improve player performance. For this project, we worked closely with the Los Angeles Dodgers to develop a mobile app and API using deep-learning to extract patterns in player positions that can be used to improve performance. Our app enables coaches and players at the professional and amateur levels to use our model on uploaded video clips of players to better understand players' movements and how they relate to play outcomes and success on the field.

column3: Gizem Incesu, Jessica Chen, Emily Redmond, Nicholas Vo
column5: Reimagining and Scaling Historical Storytelling in VR (GHA)
column6: How can historical experiences in VR be more engaging and better support cultural learning? How do we provide replay value, ie. encourage users to return to explore other sites? How do we scale this process? Our project explores each of these questions, working with Meta‚Äôs Global Historical Archive (GHA). We present a personable VR prototype experience, including interactions with culturally relevant characters, and a scalable narrative framework to apply to future historical sites. We also present an immersive VR trivia experience, which solidifies user‚Äôs historical knowledge gained through the narrative experience.

column3: Nina Du, Abla Ghaleb, Landis, Bhagirath Mehta, Mia Miao
column6: Our overarching goal is to explore the possibilities of camera mechanics in GHA and develop a camera feature that is engaging to users. Aside from the traditional expectations of a camera to take pictures and store them in an album, we also want to leverage the reality-defying aspect of VR by implementing features that allow users to collect and replicate artifacts using the camera. The test and implementation of these ‚Äònon-traditional‚Äô features will be realized through a museum-themed outer game loop where the player can curate a museum by visiting new sites, taking pictures and collecting artifacts.

column3: Ben Auslin
column5: Emulating Illusion Scaleup for Neural Network Applications‚Äã
column6: The Illusion architecture is designed to run deep learning workloads with total energy and execution time near that of an ideal single chip. The scaleup project aims to demonstrate that the architecture can keep pace with growing neural network sizes while maintaining its low overheads. Ongoing verification of a new chip that will demonstrate scaleup involves emulating the design in hardware to accelerate logic simulations. Emulation will allow the development team to test scaling the system before fabricating the design.

column3: Dhruvik Parikh
column5: Applying Determinantal Point Processes for Sample-efficient Exploration in Recommender Systems
column6: The "cold start" or new user problem has long plagued recommender systems. In order to resolve this problem before a user churns, exploration mechanisms are applied to learn the user's preferences in as few interactions as possible. This project introduces a novel exploration mechanism based on determinantal point processes that results in more sample-efficient exploration. It also introduces a standardized testing pipeline for exploration mechanisms based on the MovieLens dataset and a baseline Deep Q-Learning model.

Our platform will serve as a tool where users will no longer need to make calculations themselves, but simply take a picture of the receipt and select other users to share the payment with. Users will no longer have to overpay for that one friend that orders too much. We strive to provide consumers with a nuanced approach to bill splitting amongst friends.

column3: David Huang, Prof. David Kim (advisor), Prof. Serena Yeung (advisor)
column4: Prof. David Kim (advisor), Prof. Serena Yeung (advisor)
column5: Transformer for Non-Accidental Trauma Prediction from Electronic Health Records
column6: Non-accidental trauma (NAT) includes diagnoses such as domestic violence, assault, poisoning, and abuse. In this project, we developed a transformer-based model that uses electronic health record data to predict future diagnosis of NAT. Our model outperforms XGBoost and current state-of-the-art deep learning methods. Key to its performance was the use of a pretraining task for last visit summarization as well as incorporation of demographic and procedural features.
